parameter, with k the intrinsic permeability, ¬µ the viscosity, Œ¶ the porosity of the porous
material, H the height of the obstacle, œÅ the fluid density and u‚àû the main uniform fluid
flow velocity. The main advantage of this method is that it needs neither the mesh to fit the
boundaries nor to specify no-slip boundary conditions. In this study we set H = œÅ = u‚àû = 1
and we recall that the porosity Œ¶ is close to 1 as imposed by the Brinkman equation [22].
Therefore Œª essentially depends, in the inverse proportion, on the intrinsic permeability k of
the medium. We fix Œª to 0 in the fluid region and to 108 in the solid region.

2.2

Numerical resolution

To discretize the penalized vorticity equations (3)-(4) we use in this work a semi-Lagrangian
vortex method. The flow is discretized onto particles that carry the physical flow properties
and the resolution of the governing equations is based on a viscous splitting algorithm, which
consists at each time step to successively solve the following equations :
